<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-186-028  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 186 028.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Feb 19 1990 v9 n4 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>RingMaster bridge cracks whip to realize bandwidth capabilities.andO;(FiberCom Inc.'s fiber-optic bridge) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Olsen, Florence.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   FiberCom Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   FiberCom RingMaster 7200 (Bridge device) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Fiber Distributed Data Interface StandardBridges (Connector)Packet SwitchingLocal Area NetworksEthernetToken Ring NetworksFiber Optics.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>RingMaster Bridge Cracks Whip To Realize Bandwidth CapabilitiesandM;FiberCom Inc. has introduced a fiber-optic bridge that can keep pace with thespeed of 100-megabit/sec packet-switched networks.andM;The RingMaster bridge will allow federal and military users to realize thetrue bandwidth potential of Fiber Distributed Data Interface standardnetworks, said Gary Gallagher, vice president of marketing for the Roanoke,Va., communications company.andM;FiberCom introduced the new technology at the recent Communications Networksconference in Washington, where many vendors announced products built to theFDDI standard.andM;FiberCom has sold fiber-optic Ethernet products to the FBI, CentralIntelligence Agency and military installations.andP;  The company also has acontract to develop and manufacture the FDDI ring concentrator for NASA'sspace station Freedom.andM;The FiberCom news followed recent FDDI announcements from Sun MicrosystemsInc. and Apollo Computer Inc.andP;  Both companies have said they will make FDDIcontrollers, a necessary component of FDDI network devices.andP;  Other companiesare expected to follow suit this year.andM;Gallagher said in polling FiberCom's customer base, which is largely federal,he found &quot;almost to a person&quot; the plan is to move file servers to an FDDIbackbone as soon as possible.andM;In addition to the greater bandwidth and fault-tolerance the FiberComRingMaster bridge supports, it also permits centralized network managementfrom an FDDI network backbone, using the Simple Network Management Protocolstandard.andM;The bridge moves data at the maximum rate required by FDDI -- 500,000 packetsper second -- and remakes incoming packets into native FDDI packets.andM;FiberCom's RingMaster bridge connects up to four subnetworks -- Ethernet,token-ring or FDDI -- to an FDDI backbone, which is a dual, counter-rotatingring extending up to 100 kilometers.andM;The RingMaster bridge is $15,000 per subnetwork connection.andP;  FiberCom willbegin shipping the RingMaster in the second quarter.andO;</TEXT></DOC>